label chapter7:

    # [Scene: Rehabilitated Quay | Dawn]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm strings with soft percussion; a rising, steady motif]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmur of voices, the creak of boats, distant gulls settling]
    "You wake to the sound of the town breathing—slow, deliberate exhalations after a night of work. The repairs finished in the dark hold, but the smell tells you more than the sight: coffee and citrus from"
    "Elena Navarro's package, the iron of nails, and under it all the wet, mineral scent of mud where new saplings have been pressed into place. Hands that once trembled with urgency now cup tools with practiced"
    "steadiness."
    show aria_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_navarro "We did more than hold them back. We made them partners."
    "You say it into the cool morning and feel Mateo at your shoulder, steady as scaffolding. He smells faintly of diesel and the sea, the scent of someone who sleeps where work calls him. His arm"
    "brushes yours—a soft, ordinary contact that carries years of shared shifts and last-minute plans—then stays."
    show mateo_hale at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_hale "We did. And we did it with people who would have been left out of the plans."
    "His eyes catch the lines where engineered modules meet the mangrove roots you helped map out. There's a neatness to his gaze—he notices joints and tolerances the way other people notice faces—but there's something else now, a loosened attention that rests on you rather than on the schematic."

    mateo_hale "They wanted to know the math. You gave them the story behind the math."
    "Elena Navarro is there, passing out fried citrus parcels like medals. She presses one into your hands with a clap that lights your ribs the way sunlight threads through the greenhouse canopy. Sora Lin works the"
    "crowd nearby, paint on their fingers, laughing with a group of volunteers while watching the modular panels flex against the swell. Dr. Kavir Singh moves among the sensors, eyes sharp, adjusting calibrations as if the instruments"
    "themselves were breathing easier."
    show dr_kavir_singh at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_kavir_singh "Data looks stable across the tide gauge. The hybrid nodes smoothed the peak surge by—' (he checks his tablet, then lets the number slide) '—enough that 48 households weren't exposed. That matters."
    "You let the figure sit like a small, solid stone in your chest. Numbers are not everything—never were—but they keep conversations honest in rooms where promises can be slippery. You trained for this: to translate the"
    "truth of instruments into language a mayor, a fisher, a teenager with paint on their knuckles can hold."

    menu:
        "Thank Mateo for staying through the night":
            "You take his hand in both of yours. His fingers are warm; he squeezes back, brief and certain. A small smile nudges his mouth—private, satisfied."
        "Go speak to Elena first":
            "You fold into Elena Navarro's orbit. She fusses and feeds you another parcel, fussing more about your shoulders than the plan. Her approval lands like a benediction, spurting courage into your chest."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    "You walk the line where new engineering meets new planting, feeling the texture change beneath your boots—from grit and concrete to soft, mucky earth. Volunteers point to a spot where a panel and a root tangle"
    "like two hands learning to hold. A child runs up, earnest and breathless, and asks if she can plant another seedling. You tell her yes, and she dives in, her small knees streaked with mud."
    hide aria_navarro
    show sora_lin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    sora_lin "You saw how they argued, then sat with each other. They learned to hold more than one plan."
    "Sora's grin is a wild thing, and for a second you want to prod them—ask if the freedom songs and painted banners ever felt like compromise. But Sora's eyes flick to Mateo and then to you, unreadable for a heartbeat before they fold back into warmth."

    sora_lin "I'm proud, you know. Of this mess of a town."
    "Pride comes in many weights. Yours is heavier with debt ledgers and council minutes and the small, private cost of every sleepless negotiation. But it is also buoyed by this: children, elders, and engineers standing at the same tide-line, deciding together how to keep dawns like this."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Greenhouse & Community Rooftop | Late Afternoon]
    hide mateo_hale
    hide dr_kavir_singh
    hide sora_lin

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A mellow instrumental guitar with distant ocean percussion]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Leaves brushing, the distant call of a vendor, a soft breeze through the greenhouse plastic]
    "You and Mateo escape the crowd and climb to the rooftop greenhouse—an island of warm soil and quiet. The city below is a palette of small movements; up here the air smells of basil and damp"
    "earth. You lean against a pallet bench. Mateo takes off his jacket and runs a hand through his hair, the engineer's armor gone for a moment."
    show mateo_hale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_hale "You could have taken the grant. It would have made scaling faster, made the modules more ubiquitous in other towns."
    "You feel the question arrive and settle in your mouth. The grant was real money, real reach—an outside research fund with strings that ripple into governance. Everyone with a pulse had an opinion the day the letter arrived. You turned it over in your head until it wore thin."
    show aria_navarro at right:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_navarro "It would've been faster. But faster for whom? If the council controlling the rollout isn't rooted here, the priorities shift. I can't—' (you pause, because the line between principle and stubbornness has thinned into the same rope) 'I can't hand our stewardship to a ledger."
    "Mateo watches you, the expression in his eyes not an engineer's calculation but something closer to a barometer—sensitive to pressure. There is a risk in saying no: funds sacrificed, opportunities foregone, another city rising faster because"
    "it took the money and buried local voices. But there's also a gain: autonomy retained, practices that honor elders and builders and children all at once."

    mateo_hale "You did the hard thing. And you convinced enough people to walk it with you."
    "He reaches for your hand without asking. His fingers interlace with yours in a knot that's comfortable and deliberate. The city hums below you like a safe machine. For the first time since you returned from your studies, the future doesn't feel like an algebra problem you must solve alone."

    mateo_hale "I still think in margins and tolerances. But I've learned to see the margins people live in. I'll help enforce them—politically, practically. You're not bearing that alone anymore."

    aria_navarro "Good. Because I'm tired of carrying things I can't set down."

    menu:
        "Lean forward and say it out loud—'Let's make a life here.'":
            "You breathe the words and hand them across the space between you. Mateo's face opens—relief, surprise, and something like a vow. He says, 'Yes.' No fanfare; just a steady, slow yes that fits like a finally-found glove."
        "Keep it simple—squeeze his hand and promise to keep building":
            "You squeeze back. The promise lands shaped like a tool: practical, steady. Mateo nods, eyes wet with something he won't name, and sets a tentative plan—to wake early tomorrow and go over maintenance schedules. Love as action, not only speech."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    "The two of you sit like that for a long time, the sun sliding lower, the harbor reflecting the molten light. You think of Elena Navarro at the quay, of Dr. Kavir Singh's steady eyes, of"
    "Sora's fierce paint-streaked grin. The town needed a structure, and it needed song. The hybrid you helped build now carries both."
    # [Scene: The Tidal Lab | Evening — Council Signing]
    hide mateo_hale
    hide aria_navarro

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low choral notes that resolve into a hopeful major chord]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Pens scratching, the soft shuffle of paperwork, a distant, contained cheer from the quay]
    "Tonight, Mayor Isla Cortez seats the stewardship council at the long table. The room smells of ink and polishing oil and something home-cooked that someone set out to keep energy up. Dr. Kavir Singh presents a"
    "final model: modular seawalls that flex with tide predictions, integrated nodes that can be deployed by local crews, and a five-year plan for aggressive mangrove and seagrass restoration led by the newly formed council."
    show mayor_isla_cortez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_isla_cortez "This council will have veto power over external contracts concerning the shoreline. Funding will be routed through municipal oversight with community representation. We will pilot the hybrid modules in three sectors and expand based on outcomes."
    "Hands pass the charter. You sign not as a scientist bowing to a bureaucratic line, but as a community member anchoring the future in a document you can point to when memory fractures. The seal is"
    "small and ordinary, but when it presses down you feel the weight of a years-long argument sink into the wood like a nail."
    show dr_kavir_singh at right:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_kavir_singh "We'll open access to our datasets and keep a rotating advisory seat from the lab. Transparency keeps misuse from growing in the dark."
    "Sora stands a bit apart, paint on their knuckles. Their expression is...complex. You can't tell if relief outweighs suspicion or if both fit in the same chest. They come forward when the formalities end and presses your shoulder in that quick, unsentimental way that means more than any speech."
    show sora_lin at center:
        zoom 0.7

    sora_lin "You made them listen. And you made sure they had to involve us. Don't let them forget how to sing."
    "Elena Navarro bolts a look at you that is both accusation and benediction—because sacrifices were made and someone has to be strong enough to carry them. She winks, and you want to cry, so you focus"
    "on the small, practical things: who will rotate the maintenance crews, where the seedlings will be stored, which neighbors need help rebuilding foundations."
    hide mayor_isla_cortez
    show mateo_hale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_hale "You'll have my badge on every deployment form."
    "You let him be adamant in the way of people who make lists and keep promises. The hybrid system is not perfect. There are houses that cannot be saved and stories that won't have a continued"
    "chapter on this coastline. But the system you and the town forged buys time and breath and, perhaps most importantly, autonomy."

    menu:
        "Address the council with a short speech":
            "You stand and speak, voice steady with evidence and memory. You thank the volunteers, call out those who worked through the night, and ask the council to remember the people behind every number. The room quiets, and you can see that the words landed."
        "Let Mateo speak for you both; stand and listen":
            "Mateo stands instead, and his thank-you is precise and warm, mentioning logistics and oversight and the dignity of keeping decisions local. When he finishes, your hand finds his, and together you sit back down—two people who can share the light of a small victory."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    "The final signatures dry. A small cheer rises, then settles into low conversation as people plan the work days ahead. Outside, the sea is a steady slate; inside, the lab hums with bright screens and the occasional laugh that comes from exhaustion and relief."

    mateo_hale "You turned down the grant, and it still worked."
    hide dr_kavir_singh
    show aria_navarro at right:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_navarro "We built trust into infrastructure."
    "You walk out into a night that smells of salt and cooling metal. Lanterns sway above the quay where volunteers wash tools. Somewhere, someone plays a bowed instrument low and long. The town is not unbroken,"
    "but it is moving; it breathes as an organism taught to carry both repair and regrowth."
    hide sora_lin
    show dr_kavir_singh at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_kavir_singh "We should write up the methodology. Other towns will want to emulate the hybrid model—on their terms."
    "You nod. The thought of other places adopting this—of the model being tested, cited, and adapted—sends a small thrill through you. Not because of acclaim, but because the stewardship council's charter includes clauses for shared access and for refused imposition. That was the part you fought hardest for."
    hide mateo_hale
    show elena_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_navarro "You kept this home ours."
    "Your face folds into hers and you feel the brittle tension of months loosen. You are tired. You are relieved. You are terrified in small, sensible ways about the next storm season—because storms will come—but for"
    "now the town holds, and the people who live here have a seat at the table to argue, fix, and plant their future."
    hide aria_navarro
    show mateo_hale at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_hale "Stay tonight?"
    "You look at him—at the man who bolts structures and, now unmistakably, who wants to build a life beside you. The greenhouse lights blink behind you like stars pinned to plastic. The quay hums."
    hide dr_kavir_singh
    show aria_navarro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_navarro "Yes."
    "You walk back toward the harbor together, hands clasped like a plan that will be revised and kept. The hybrid system isn't a perfect answer—there are compromises and losses written into its margins—but it is proof"
    "that a town can choose how it survives. That choice, given back to the people who live the tides every morning, is the core of your work."
    hide elena_navarro
    hide mateo_hale
    hide aria_navarro

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The string motif swells into a warm, resolving chord]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Waves, distant laughter, a single gull calling once and falling silent]
    "You came back to this place to save it, and in the saving you learned the shape of partnership. You kept the control local. You chose people over speed where it mattered. You and Mateo—together with"
    "a town that is both stubborn and generous—have made a model that might outlast both of you."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade into a gentle, conclusive hum]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_5 at full_bg

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_6 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
